docs.abstract: The North Carolina Republican is seeking to clear himself through an ethics investigation after the disclosure that he sold most of his holdings before the market tumbled.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The nation remained fixated on the final acts of the impeachment drama in early February, but as the Senate prepared to acquit President Trump, Senator Richard M. Burr, Republican of North Carolina and the chairman of the Intelligence Committee, already had his eye on a troubling new threat: the coronavirus.

headline.main: Stock Sales by Senator Richard Burr Ignite Political Uproar
headline.print_headline: Stock Sales by Senator Stir a Political Uproar

byline.original: By Eric Lipton, Nicholas Fandos, Sharon LaFraniere and Julian E. Barnes

docs.abstract: If the administration had reacted to the ventilator shortage in February, a private sector effort starting now might have made lifesaving equipment in mid- to late April. Now it is unlikely to be before June.
docs.snippet: If the administration had reacted to the ventilator shortage in February, a private sector effort starting now might have made lifesaving equipment in mid- to late April. Now it is unlikely to be before June.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When Ford’s chief executive, Jim Hackett, announced on Tuesday that the carmaker would team up with General Electric to build ventilators, he tempered the good news with a note of caution: “We’re talking about early June.”

headline.main: Slow Response to the Coronavirus Measured in Lost Opportunity
headline.print_headline: A Slow Response, Measured in Nonexistent Tests, Masks and Ventilators

byline.original: By David E. Sanger, Zolan Kanno-Youngs and Ana Swanson

docs.abstract: The briefing has given him a unique perch from which he can talk about the pandemic and try to project leadership after initially minimizing it. But that’s not always what he has done.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s campaign rallies have been canceled for the foreseeable future. His noisy back-and-forths with reporters on the South Lawn, half drowned out by the whir of Marine One behind him, have also disappeared.

headline.main: In Daily Coronavirus Briefing, Trump Tries to Redefine Himself
headline.print_headline: Rallies Canceled, Trump Moves Stage to the Briefing Room

docs.abstract: The online platform could allow physicians to upload patient data on how malaria drugs perform on coronavirus patients.
docs.snippet: The online platform could allow physicians to upload patient data on how malaria drugs perform on coronavirus patients.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The White House is preparing to use software provided by the technology giant Oracle to promote unproven coronavirus treatments, including a pair of malaria drugs publicized by President Trump, potentially before the government approves their use for the outbreak, according to five senior administration officials and others familiar with the plans.

headline.main: Oracle Providing White House With Software to Study Unproven Coronavirus Drugs
headline.print_headline: Oracle Is Enlisted by the White House  To Aid in the Study of Unproven Drugs

byline.original: By Noah Weiland and Maggie Haberman

docs.abstract: Republicans sought to put their imprint on an emerging economic stabilization package of $1 trillion, unveiling a bill that includes tax cuts and loans to businesses and would curtail paid leave.
docs.snippet: Republicans sought to put their imprint on an emerging economic stabilization package of $1 trillion, unveiling a bill that includes tax cuts and loans to businesses and would curtail paid leave.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The White House and lawmakers scrambled on Thursday to flesh out details of a $1 trillion economic stabilization plan to help workers and businesses weather a potentially deep recession, negotiating over the size and scope of direct payments to millions of people and aid for companies facing devastation in the coronavirus pandemic.

headline.main: Senate Rescue Package Includes Corporate Tax Cuts and $1,200 Checks
headline.print_headline: Senate Rescue Bill Includes Corporate Tax Cuts and $1,200 Checks

byline.original: By Emily Cochrane, Jim Tankersley and Alan Rappeport

docs.abstract: The Federal Reserve said it would backstop money market funds that invested in municipal bonds, making sure they can meet redemptions.
docs.snippet: The Federal Reserve said it would backstop money market funds that invested in municipal bonds, making sure they can meet redemptions.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Federal Reserve tiptoed into the market for municipal debt on Friday, a small move that economists, lawmakers and state treasurers say should be expanded as the coronavirus places huge financial pressure on local governments.

headline.main: Fed Backstops Corner of Municipal Debt Markets Amid Calls for Support
headline.print_headline: Central Bank Backstops a Corner of Municipal Debt Markets

docs.abstract: The court ruled in cases on the insanity defense, race discrimination and copyright infringement.
docs.snippet: The court ruled in cases on the insanity defense, race discrimination and copyright infringement.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In a series of decisions, the Supreme Court on Monday ruled that states may abolish a common form of the insanity defense, that an entrepreneur suing Comcast for race discrimination must meet a demanding standard and that states are immune from claims of copyright infringement.

headline.main: Back at Work but Not on the Bench, Supreme Court Issues 3 Major Opinions
headline.print_headline: Justices Back at Work, But Not on the Bench

docs.abstract: Many experts warn that an international health and economic crisis calls for more cooperation, not confrontation, between Washington and Beijing.
docs.snippet: Many experts warn that an international health and economic crisis calls for more cooperation, not confrontation, between Washington and Beijing.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When President Trump took the podium at the White House briefing room one afternoon last week, his prepared remarks included a reference to the “corona virus.” But a close-up photograph revealed that Mr. Trump had used one of his signature Sharpies to cross out the word “corona,” changing the phrase to “Chinese virus.”

headline.main: Coronavirus Drives the U.S. and China Deeper Into Global Power Struggle
headline.print_headline: Confrontation Is Winning Out Over Cooperation in Face of a Pandemic

byline.original: By Michael Crowley, Edward Wong and Lara Jakes

docs.abstract: Democrats voted against moving forward on a plan expected to cost $1.8 trillion or more, seeking stronger protections for workers and stricter rules for bailed-out businesses.
docs.snippet: Democrats voted against moving forward on a plan expected to cost $1.8 trillion or more, seeking stronger protections for workers and stricter rules for bailed-out businesses.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senate Democrats on Sunday blocked action on an emerging deal to prop up an economy devastated by the coronavirus pandemic, paralyzing the progress of a nearly $2 trillion government rescue package they said failed to adequately protect workers or impose strict enough restrictions on bailed-out businesses.

headline.main: Emergency Economic Rescue Plan in Limbo as Democrats Block Action
headline.print_headline: Partisan Divide Threatens Deal On Rescue Bill

byline.original: By Emily Cochrane, Jim Tankersley and Jeanna Smialek
